Bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{for pasta} to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the pasta.

Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%grams} and fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat. > Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Sprinkle over the @mixed herbs{1%sachet} and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute} more.

Meanwhile, add the @linguine{180%grams} to your pan of boiling water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{for tossing} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

While the pasta cooks, add the @Worcester sauce{15%grams} to the beef and allow to bubble away until evaporated, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1%carton}, @red wine jus paste{15%grams}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and @water{50%ml} for the sauce.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium and simmer until the sauce has thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add a splash more water if it gets too thick. > The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the sauce has thickened, stir in the @baby spinach{40%grams} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Toss the cooked linguine through the sauce along with half the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%grams}. If it's easier, transfer everything to the #pasta saucepan{} to combine.

Taste and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} if needed. Add a splash of water if the sauce is a little too thick.

Share the herby beef linguine between your #bowls{}.

Finish with a sprinkle of the remaining hard Italian style cheese.

Enjoy!